    "spec": "# Bulk Session-Cost Helper on AnimatorApi; Spider Rig-View Migration\n\n## Intent\n\nAdd a bulk, per-session cost/token retrieval method to `AnimatorApi` and migrate Spider's rig-view cost aggregator (`enrichRigView` / `enrichRigViews`) to call it instead of reading the Animator's `sessions` book directly through The Stacks. The behavioural output of the rig-view aggregator does not change; only the data path does.\n\n## Rationale\n\nSpider's UI-facing cost-aggregation path currently reaches into another apparatus's book to compute per-rig and per-engine cost summaries. Routing that query through an Animator-owned API establishes a boundary for *derived* read-side data and lets the Animator own the shape of cost answers. This commission is the first consumer of that boundary; if the pattern proves out, later commissions can decide whether to migrate the other five Spider → `animator/sessions` read sites. Keeping scope narrow is deliberate — we earn the abstraction from a real second consumer, not from speculation.\n\n## Scope & Blast Radius\n\n- **Animator plugin (`packages/plugins/animator`).** The `AnimatorApi` interface grows one new read-side method — the first of its kind on this API, so the implementation sets precedent for future read-side helpers. Implementation, types, and unit tests all move together.\n- **Spider plugin (`packages/plugins/spider`).** The rig-view cost aggregator is the only call site that migrates. Its tests update to match the new data path but continue to exercise real book storage end-to-end (the new method must read through the same book the tests seed).\n- **Animator architecture doc (`docs/architecture/apparatus/animator.md`).** The AnimatorApi enumeration currently lists every method; it must stay in sync with the new surface.\n- **No change to `SpiderApi`, no change to persisted document shapes, no schema migration, no new package dependency** (Spider already depends on `@shardworks/animator-apparatus`).\n- **Cross-cutting concern — verify the old data path is fully gone.** After migration, `packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.ts` should contain no reference to `readBook(...'animator'...'sessions'...)`. Grep the spider package to confirm the only remaining direct-book reads against `animator/sessions` are in the five sites D3 explicitly excludes (`oculus-routes.ts`, `spider.ts`, `engines/review.ts`, `engines/piece-session.ts`, `engines/manual-merge.ts`).\n\n## Decisions\n\n| # | Decision | Default | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D1 | Return shape of the new method | **Per-session map** keyed by session id, each entry carrying `costUsd` and optional `inputTokens` / `outputTokens`. Missing ids are absent keys. | Rig-view needs both a rig-level total and a per-engine breakdown; aggregate-only cannot cover both without extra round-trips or leaving half the coupling in place. |\n| D2 | Where the method lives | On `AnimatorApi` (types in the animator plugin's public type module; implementation inside the existing `createAnimator()` factory). | The animator factory already has the sessions book handle in closure scope; no new apparatus needed for a single-method read surface. |\n| D3 | Does this commission also migrate other Spider → `animator/sessions` reads? | **Narrow — rig-view only.** The transcript handler, `tryCollect`, and the three engine collect sites keep their direct `readBook` reads. | Earn the pattern from a second consumer before expanding; the other five sites are speculation until rig-view proves out. |\n| D4 | Proceed at all? | **Proceed.** | The patron commissioning the observation overrides the original author's \"not worth it\" hedge. |\n| D5 | Is the token-formatter `'en-US'` observation still actionable? | **Excluded.** S2 ships no code changes. | `spider.js` already calls `toLocaleString('en-US')` and a regex test pins that behaviour. Cross-dashboard convergence was scoped out by the parent commission. |\n| D6 | Behaviour when requested session ids are not found | **Silent-skip.** Missing ids are omitted from the returned map and not counted in any aggregation the caller composes. | Preserves the existing `enrichRigView` semantic (missing = zero contribution), which is codified in current tests; no caller today distinguishes absent from zero. |\n\n## Acceptance Signal\n\n1. **New method exists on `AnimatorApi`** with the per-session-map return shape per D1, and is exported through the animator plugin's public types so Spider can name it from its own package.\n2. **Spider's rig-view aggregator calls the new method** instead of `stacks.readBook('animator', 'sessions')`. Grep `packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.ts` for `readBook` and `animator.*sessions` — both should come up empty.\n3. **Aggregation output for rig-view is unchanged.** Existing `rig-view.test.ts` cases (cost sums, missing-session-as-zero, non-terminal session inclusion, no-tokenUsage omission, multi-rig fan-out) all pass without loosening their assertions. If an assertion needs to change to match a legitimate data-path difference, that is a signal the migration changed observable behaviour and must be investigated.\n4. **Missing session ids do not throw** — both in the new method and at the rig-view call site. A test exists on the animator side that exercises the `unknown id` case and asserts the returned map omits that key.\n5. **D3 is respected.** Grep the spider package for `readBook` calls against `animator` / `sessions`: the five sites listed in D3 remain; the rig-view site is gone. No additional sites have been migrated or regressed.\n6. **`docs/architecture/apparatus/animator.md`** lists the new method in the AnimatorApi enumeration.\n7. **Full workspace typecheck and test suite pass** (`pnpm -w typecheck`, `pnpm -w test`).\n\n## Existing Patterns\n\n- **AnimatorApi shape.** Read the existing methods (`summon`, `animate`, `subscribeToSession`, `cancel`) in `packages/plugins/animator/src/types.ts` and their implementations inside `createAnimator()` in `packages/plugins/animator/src/animator.ts`. Follow the naming and JSDoc conventions already established there. Note this is the *first* read-side method on this API — your choice of naming and parameter style becomes the precedent for future read-side helpers.\n- **Bulk queries on Stacks.** `StacksApi.book<T>().find({ where: [['id', 'IN', ids]] })` is the idiomatic bulk-by-id pattern in this monorepo. The current rig-view code does per-id `Promise.all(...get...)`; the new method is the right place to consolidate that into a single query on the animator side.\n- **Graceful-missing semantics to preserve.** `packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.ts` (particularly the `.catch(() => null)` + `session?.costUsd ?? 0` chain) and its tests (`packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.test.ts:148-163`) codify the \"missing = zero contribution\" semantic. The new method's silent-skip contract serves the same intent; the rig-view call site should stay robust to absent map entries without additional guarding beyond what the shape already gives.\n- **Test style for animator methods.** `packages/plugins/animator/src/animator.test.ts` establishes the pattern: `createStacksApparatus` + `MemoryBackend`, seed docs via `stacks.readBook<SessionDoc>('animator', 'sessions')` (or its writable counterpart), then exercise `AnimatorApi` methods through the public surface. Follow this pattern — do not stub the internals.\n- **Test style for rig-view.** `packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.test.ts` seeds SessionDocs by writing directly to the animator book. This must keep working after migration: the new method must read from the same book the tests write to. **Do not** replace the tests' real-storage path with an `AnimatorApi` stub — end-to-end coverage through real storage is the reason these tests are trustworthy.\n- **Where the animator book handle lives.** Inside `createAnimator()` in `animator.ts`, the sessions book is assigned to a closure var during `start()`. The new read method can use the same handle; no new wiring is required.\n\n## What NOT To Do\n\n- **Do not migrate the other Spider → `animator/sessions` read sites.** The transcript handler in `oculus-routes.ts`, `tryCollect` in `spider.ts`, and the three engine collect sites (`engines/review.ts`, `engines/piece-session.ts`, `engines/manual-merge.ts`) stay on direct `readBook` per D3. Resist the urge to \"clean them up while you're here\" — that's the next commission's job if the pattern proves out.\n- **Do not touch Spider's `spider.js` token formatter or its test.** S2 is closed per D5; there is no change to make there.\n- **Do not extend the `'en-US'` locale convention to Parlour or Astrolabe dashboards.** That is a separate cross-dashboard concern.\n- **Do not add cross-apparatus tie-break guidance to `parlour.md` or `spider.md`.** The tension between \"apparatus API\" and \"direct readBook\" for cross-plugin data access is a real architectural question, but it is outside this commission.\n- **Do not introduce caching or memoisation on the new method.** The rig-view tests assume the method reads live book state; any caching layer would make them flaky or require test refactors outside scope.\n- **Do not change `SpiderApi`, `RigDoc`, `RigView`, or any persisted document shape.** The migration is internal to the rig-view aggregator's data path.\n- **Do not introduce a separate `AnimatorReadApi` or other new apparatus.** Per D2 the method lives on the existing `AnimatorApi`.\n- **Do not add an `explicit-null` / \"every id represented\" variant.** Per D6 missing ids are absent keys. Callers (today, just rig-view) compose zero-contribution from map absence.\n\n<task-manifest>\n  <task id=\"t1\">\n    <name>Declare the new read-side method on AnimatorApi</name>\n    <files>packages/plugins/animator/src/types.ts (AnimatorApi interface and any supporting type exports consumed by Spider)</files>\n    <action>Extend the public AnimatorApi type surface with a single new read-side method per D1 (bulk per-session cost/token lookup keyed by session id; missing ids absent from the result). Name it, document it with JSDoc consistent with the existing methods in the same file, and ensure any result-shape type it introduces is exported so that Spider can consume it from the animator plugin's public entry point. Keep naming and parameter conventions consistent with the other methods on AnimatorApi — this is the first read-side method, so your choices set the precedent.</action>\n    <verify>pnpm -w typecheck</verify>\n    <done>AnimatorApi has a new method declaration; the return-shape type is exported; the workspace typechecks (it will fail where Spider's rig-view still uses the old path — that's fine, later tasks fix it).</done>\n  </task>\n\n  <task id=\"t2\">\n    <name>Implement the new method in createAnimator()</name>\n    <files>packages/plugins/animator/src/animator.ts (inside createAnimator)</files>\n    <action>Implement the method using the sessions book handle already available in the factory's closure scope. Use a single bulk query against the animator sessions book (Stacks IN-predicate) rather than per-id reads, so the implementation scales better than the path it replaces. Honour D6: session ids not present in the book are omitted from the returned map. Preserve the existing convention in this file for how the read-path handles an empty-input case (returning an empty map without a round-trip is acceptable). Follow the existing code's error-handling conventions for Stacks interactions on read paths — do not introduce new try/catch patterns beyond what the rest of the file uses.</action>\n    <verify>pnpm -w typecheck</verify>\n    <done>The method is implemented and the animator package typechecks cleanly on its own; no per-id round-trip loop; missing ids absent from the returned map.</done>\n  </task>\n\n  <task id=\"t3\">\n    <name>Cover the new method with animator tests</name>\n    <files>packages/plugins/animator/src/animator.test.ts</files>\n    <action>Add tests that exercise: (a) the happy path — a handful of seeded session docs, method returns the expected per-id entries; (b) the missing-id path — requesting an id that does not exist in the sessions book results in an absent key, no throw (D6); (c) the mixed-input path — some present, some absent, partial-result map; (d) the optional-token path — a session with costUsd but without tokenUsage returns a cost-only entry (mirrors the omit-when-absent rig-view behaviour). Use the existing test harness pattern in this file (Stacks + MemoryBackend, seed via the sessions book, exercise the public AnimatorApi).</action>\n    <verify>pnpm --filter @shardworks/animator-apparatus test</verify>\n    <done>Animator package tests pass including the new method's cases.</done>\n  </task>\n\n  <task id=\"t4\">\n    <name>Migrate Spider's rig-view aggregator to the new method</name>\n    <files>packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.ts; packages/plugins/spider/src/rig-view.test.ts</files>\n    <action>Replace the direct `stacks.readBook('animator', 'sessions')` read path in enrichRigView / enrichRigViews with a single call to the new AnimatorApi method, gathered through the same apparatus-resolution mechanism Spider already uses for other animator interactions (`guild().apparatus<AnimatorApi>('animator')` or whatever the established pattern in this package is — follow it; do not invent a new resolution path). Preserve all observable behaviour: rig-level costSummary, per-engine engineCosts, the `anyTokenUsage` flag logic for omitting totals, the zero-contribution-on-missing semantic. Update rig-view.test.ts only where necessary to keep tests passing end-to-end through real book storage — tests must continue to seed SessionDocs by writing to the animator sessions book directly (do not stub AnimatorApi). If an existing assertion has to change to match legitimate data-path differences, flag that as a red flag — the migration should not alter observable aggregation output.</action>\n    <verify>pnpm --filter @shardworks/spider-apparatus test</verify>\n    <done>rig-view.ts no longer references the animator sessions book directly; all six existing rig-view test cases still pass; no stubbing of AnimatorApi introduced.</done>\n  </task>\n\n  <task id=\"t5\">\n    <name>Confirm D3 scope fence and the full workspace build</name>\n    <files>packages/plugins/spider/src (verification only — no edits expected); entire workspace</files>\n    <action>Verify the scope fence held: grep the spider package for direct reads of the animator sessions book and confirm only the five D3-excluded sites remain (oculus-routes.ts, spider.ts, engines/review.ts, engines/piece-session.ts, engines/manual-merge.ts). Confirm rig-view.ts is no longer in the match set. Run the full workspace typecheck and test suite to catch any cross-package regressions. If a test beyond rig-view breaks, diagnose before editing — the migration should not affect unrelated behaviour.</action>\n    <verify>grep -rn \"readBook.*animator.*sessions\\|readBook.*'animator'.*'sessions'\" packages/plugins/spider/src &amp;&amp; pnpm -w typecheck &amp;&amp; pnpm -w test</verify>\n    <done>Grep shows exactly the five D3-excluded sites (no rig-view.ts entry); workspace typecheck and tests pass.</done>\n  </task>\n\n  <task id=\"t6\">\n    <name>Update the Animator architecture doc</name>\n    <files>docs/architecture/apparatus/animator.md</files>\n    <action>Add an entry for the new method to the AnimatorApi enumeration section of the doc (around the block that currently lists summon / animate / subscribeToSession / cancel). Match the existing entries' format — name, purpose, parameter summary, return summary. Note in the purpose line that this is the first read-side helper on AnimatorApi and is used by Spider's rig-view cost aggregation. Do not expand into tie-break guidance between apparatus APIs and direct readBook — that is out of scope.</action>\n    <verify>grep -n \"AnimatorApi\\|sessions\" docs/architecture/apparatus/animator.md</verify>\n    <done>The doc's AnimatorApi section enumerates the new method alongside the existing four; the description is consistent in style with the existing entries.</done>\n  </task>\n</task-manifest>\n"
